the soliloquy. The study thus offers a new reading of the poems by Shakespeare and Donne by analysing them, in different ways, as staged dialogues within the soul. It contributes to research on the soliloquy as much as on concepts of inwardness during the early modern period. The book is aimed at readers studying early modern literature and culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish dramay17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish drama. 0aEnglish poetryyEarly modern, 1500-1700. 4aShakespeare 2019. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh  adrama.  ainteriority.  aperformance.  apoetry.  apsychomachia.  asoliloquy.  asoul.1 aZirker, Angelika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2019 eBook-Packagez978311128249740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152613330440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526133304423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526133304/original  a978-3-11-128249-7  Manchester University Press 2019 eBook-Packageb2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles